
[1]tuition

   TUI'TION, n. [L. tuitio, from tueor, to see, behold, protect, &c; L.
   duco, to lead.]

   1. Guardianship; superintending care over a young person; the
   particular watch and care of a tutor or guardian over his pupil or
   ward.

   2. More especially, instruction; the act or business of teaching the
   various branches of learning. We place our children under the
   preceptors of academies for tuition. [This is now the common
   acceptation of the word.]

   3. The money paid for instruction. In our colleges, the tuition is from
   thirty to forty dollars a year.
